==== tan ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double tan( double arg );
</source>
}}

The tan() function returns the tangent of ''arg'', where ''arg'' is given in radians. If ''arg'' is infinite, tan() will return NAN and raise a floating-point exception.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/acos|acos]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/asin|asin]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atan|atan]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atan2|atan2]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/cos|cos]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/cosh|cosh]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sin|sin]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sinh|sinh]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/tanh|tanh]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== tanh ====
{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double tanh( double arg );
</source>
}}


<source lang="c">
/*example*/
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>
int main (){
	double c, p;
	c = log(2.0);
	p = tanh (c);
	printf ("The hyperbolic tangent of %lf is %lf.\n", c, p );
return 0;
}
</source>

The function tanh() returns the hyperbolic tangent of ''arg''.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/acos|acos]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/asin|asin]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atan|atan]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/atan2|atan2]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/cos|cos]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/cosh|cosh]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sin|sin]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sinh|sinh]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/tan|tan]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== exp ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double exp( double arg );
</source>
}}

The exp() function returns e (2.7182818) raised to the ''arg''th power.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/log|log]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/pow|pow]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/sqrt|sqrt]]

