==== frexp ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double frexp( double num, int* exp );
</source>
}}

The function frexp() is used to decompose ''num'' into two parts: a mantissa between 0.5 and 1 (returned by the function) and an exponent returned as ''exp''. Scientific notation works like this:

<source lang=cpp>
num = mantissa * (2 ^ exp)   
</source>

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/ldexp|ldexp]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/modf|modf]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== ldexp ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double ldexp( double num, int exp );
</source>
}}

The ldexp() function returns ''num'' * (2 ^ ''exp''). And get this: if an overflow occurs, '''HUGE_VAL''' is returned.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/frexp|frexp]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/modf|modf]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

==== modf ====

{{C++ Programming/Syntax|
<source lang=cpp>
#include <cmath>
double modf( double num, double *i );
</source>
}}

The function modf() splits ''num'' into its integer and fraction parts. It returns the fractional part and loads the integer part into ''i''.

;Related topics: [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/frexp|frexp]] - [[C++ Programming/Code/Standard C Library/Functions/ldexp|ldexp]]

[[Category:{{FULLBOOKNAME}}|{{SUBPAGENAME}}]]

